\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      It was an ordinary gray British Ford, the spartan economy model with right-hand drive customary in Ireland. John Roe O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 Neill would remember the driver\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s brown-sweatered right arm resting on the car\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s windo\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
wsill in the cloud-filtered light of that Dublin afternoon. A nightmare capsule of memory, it excluded everything else in the scene; just the car and that arm.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Several other surviving witnesses commented on a crumpled break in the Ford\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s left front wi\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 ng. The break had begun to rust.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      Speaking from her hospital bed, one witness said: \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 The break was a jagged thing and I was afraid someone would be cut if they brushed against it.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Two of those who recalled seeing the car come out of Lower Leeson \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
Street knew the driver casually, but only from his days in postal uniform. He was Francis Bley, a retired postman working part-time as a watchman at a building site in Dun Laoghaire. Bley left for work early every Wednesday, giving himself time to run a f
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 w errands and then pick up his wife, Tessie. On that one day each week, Tessie spent the morning doing \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 light secretarial\'94\loch\f0 
 for a betting shop in King Street. It was Tessie\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s habit to spend the rest of the day with her widowed sister who lived in a remodel\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
d gatehouse off the Dun Laoghaire bypass \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 just a few minutes out of his way.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      This was a Wednesday. May 20. Bley was on his way to pick up Tessie.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The Ford\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s left front door, although appearing undamaged by the accident that had crumpled the wing\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
, still required a twist of wire around the doorpost to keep it closed. The door rattled every time the car hit a bump.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 I heard it rattling when it turned onto St. Stephen\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s Green South,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  one witness said. \'93\loch\f0 It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s God\hich\f0 
\rquote \loch\f0 s own mercy I wasn\hich\f0 \rquote \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 t at the Grafton corner when it happened.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Bley turned right off St. Stephen\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s Green South, which put him on St. Stephen\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s Green West, hugging the left lane as he headed for Grafton Street. There were better routes for him to make his connection with \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Tessie, but this was \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 his way.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 He liked to see all the people,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Tessie said. \'93\loch\f0 God rest him, that\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s what he said he missed most when he quit the postal \hich\f0 
\endash \loch\f0 \hich\f0  all the people.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Bley, slight and wrinkled, had that skin-stretched cadaverous look that is\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
 common among certain aged Celts from the south of Ireland. He wore a soiled brown hat almost the exact shade of his patched sweater, and he drove with the patient detachment of someone who came this way often. And if the truth were known, he rather liked
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 being slowed by the heavy traffic.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      It had been cold and wet through most of spring and, while it was still cloudy, the cloud cover had thinned and there was a feeling that there might be a break in the weather. Only a few of the pedestrians carried um
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 brellas. The trees of St. Stephen\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s Green on Bley\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s right were in full leaf.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      As the Ford inched along in the congested traffic, the man watching for it from a fourth-floor window of the Irish Film Society Building nodded once in satisfaction.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Rig\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 ht on time.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Bley\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s Ford had been selected because of this Wednesday punctuality. There was also the fact that Bley did not garage his car where he and Tessie lived in Davitt Road. The Ford was parked outside beside a thick yew hedge, which could be ap
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 proached from the street along a path shielded by a parked van. There had been a van parked in this covering position the previous night. Neighbors had seen it but no one had thought to comment at the time.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 There were often vehicles parked in that pl\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 ace,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  one said. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 How were we to know?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The watcher at the Film Society Building had many names but he had been born Joseph Leo Herity. He was a small, solidly fleshy man with a long, thin face and pale, almost translucent skin. Herity wore his blond h
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 air combed straight back and hanging almost to the collar. His light brown eyes were deeply set and he had a pugged nose with prominent nostrils from which hair protruded.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      From his fourth-floor vantage, Herity commanded an overview of the entire setti\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
ng for the drama he was about to ignite. Directly across from him, the tall trees of the green formed a verdant wall enclosing the flow of vehicles and pedestrians. The Robert Emmet statue stood opposite his window and, to the left of it, there was a blac
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 k\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 -on-white sign to the public toilets. Bley\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s Ford had stopped with the traffic just to the left of Herity\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s window. A white tour bus with blue-and-red stripes down its side loomed over the small Ford. Traffic fumes were thick even at the fourth-floor leve\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 l\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 .
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Herity checked Bley\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s license number to be certain. Yes \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0  JIA-5028. Then there was the crumpled left front wing.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The traffic began to inch forward, then stopped once more.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Herity glanced left at the Grafton Street corner. He could see the \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
signs of the Toy World shop and the Irish Permanent Society on the ground floor of the red brick building soon to be taken over by the Ulster Bank. There had been some protest about that, one ragged march with a few signs, but it had died out quickly. The
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 Ulster Bank had powerful friends in the government.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Barney and his lot, Herity thought. They think we\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 re ignorant of their scheme to make a peace with the Ulster boys!
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Again, Bley\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s Ford inched toward the corner, but once more was stopped. There \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 was heavy foot traffic where Grafton took off from St. Stephen\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s Green.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      A bald-headed man in a dark blue suit had stopped almost directly beneath Herity\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s window and was examining the cinema marquee. Two young men pushing bicycles threaded their way p
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 ast the bald-headed man.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The traffic remained stopped.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Herity looked down at the top of Bley\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s car. So innocent-looking, that car. Herity had been one of the two-man team to emerge from the yew-shrouded van near Bley\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s parking spot the previous n\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 ight. In Herity\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s hands had been a molded plastic package, which they had attached like a deformed limpet under Bley\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s car. At the core of that package lay a tiny radio receiver. The transmitter sat on the windowsill in front of Herity. A small black meta\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 l\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
 rectangle, it had a thin wire antenna and two recessed toggle switches \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0  one painted yellow, the other red. Yellow armed it, red transmitted.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      A glance at his wristwatch told Herity that they were already five minutes past Zero Time. Not Bley\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s fault.\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  It was the blasted traffic.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 You can set your bloody watch by Bley,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  the leader of their selection team had said. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 The old bastard should be running a tram.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 What\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 re his politics?\'94\loch\f0  Greaves had asked.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Who cares about his politics?\'94\loch\f0  Herity \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 had countered. \'93\loch\f0 He\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s perfect and he\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
\hich\f0 ll be dying for a grand cause.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 The street\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ll be full of people,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Greaves had said. \'93\loch\f0 And there\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 
ll be tourists sure as hell is full of Brits.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 We warned \hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 em to stop the Ulster boys,\'94\loch\f0  Herity had said. Greaves c\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 ould be an old woman sometimes! \'93\loch\f0 
They know what to expect when they don\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 t listen to us.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      It was settled then. And now Bley\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s car was inching once more toward the Grafton Street corner, toward the mass of pedestrians, including the possible tourists.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0     John Roe O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
Neill, his wife, Mary, and their five-year-old twins, Kevin and Mairead, could have been classified as tourists, although John expected to be six months in Ireland while completing the research called for under his grant from the Pastermorn
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 Foundation of New Haven, Conn.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 An Overview of Irish Genetic Research.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      He thought the title pompous, but it was only a cover. The real research was into the acceptance of the new genetics by a Roman Catholic society, whether such a society had t\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
aken a position to cope with the explosive potentials in molecular biology.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The project was much on his mind that Wednesday morning but necessary\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
 preparations required his attention. High on his list was the need to transfer funds from America to the Allied Irish Bank. Mary wanted to go shopping for sweaters \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 to keep our darlings warm of an evening.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 There y\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0  go,\'94\loch\f0  John teased as they left the\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Sherbourne Hotel, stepping into the rush of tourists and businessmen. \'93
\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Only four days in Ireland and already you sound like a local.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 And why not?\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  she demanded. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 And both my grandmothers from Limerick.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      They laughed, drawing a few curious star\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 es. The children tugged at Mary, anxious to be off shopping.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Ireland suited Mary, John thought. She had pale clear skin and dark blue eyes. Jet-black hair \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0 \hich\f0  \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Spanish Hair,\'94\loch\f0  her family called it \hich\f0 \endash 
\loch\f0  framed her rather round face. A sweet face. Irish skin \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
and Irish features. He bent and kissed her before leaving. It brought a blush to her face but she was pleased at his show of affection and she gave him a warm smile as they parted.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      John walked away briskly, humming to himself, amused when he recognize\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 d the tune: \'93\loch\f0 Oh What a Beautiful Mornin\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 .\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      John\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s Wednesday appointment for \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 transfer of foreign funds\'94\loch\f0 
 was at two P.M. at the Allied Irish Bank, Grafton and Chatham streets. There was a sign just inside the bank\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s entrance, white letters on black: \'93\loch\f0 N\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
on Branch Customers Upstairs.\'94\loch\f0 
 A uniformed guard led him up the stairs to the office of the bank manager, Charles Mulrain, a small, nervous man with tow-colored hair and pale blue eyes behind gold-framed glasses. Mulrain had a habit of touching the corner\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 s
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0  of his mouth with a forefinger, first left side then right, followed by a quick downward brush of his dark tie. He made a joke about having his office on the first floor, \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
what you Americans call the second floor.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 It is confusing until you catch on\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 ,\'94\loch\f0  John agreed.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Well!\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  A quick touching of lips and tie. \'93\loch\f0 You understand that we\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 d normally do this at our main office, but\'85\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 When I called, they assured me it was\'85\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 As a convenience to the customer,\'94\loch\f0  Mulrain said. He lifted a folder from\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0  his desk, glanced inside it, nodded. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
Yes, this amount\'85\loch\f0  if you\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 ll make yourself comfortable here, I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ll just get the proper forms and be right back.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Mulrain left, giving John a tight smile at the door.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      John went to the window and pulled back a h\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 eavy lace curtain to look down on Grafton Street. The sidewalks were thick with people all the way up to the arched gateway into St. Stephen\hich\f0 
