\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The pattern of change built itself slowly in John Roe O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 Neill. It set him trembling unexpectedly at odd moments, his heart pounding, sweat brea\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
king out all over his body. At such times, he thought of the old beliefs in possession. It was like that \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0  another personality taking over his flesh and nerves.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Much later, he came to a personal accommodation with this Other, even a sense of familiari\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
ty and identity. He thought of it then as partly his own making, partly a thing rising out of primal darkness, a deliberate creation for the task of revenge. Certainly, his Old Self had not been up to such a deed. The kindly teacher-of-the-young could not
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 have contemplated such a plan for an instant. The Other had to come into being first.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      As the change progressed, he came to think of himself as Nemesis revived. This Nemesis came out of Ireland\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s bloody past, out of the betrayals and murders, and even \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
carried with it a retaliation against the Celtic extermination of the First People, the Danaans, who had been in Ireland before the waves of invaders from Britain and the Continent. He saw himself then as a spokesman for all of the accumulated wrongs suff
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 red in Ireland. It was Nemesis blaring:
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Enough! Let it end!\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      But the Other asked: \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Why should Ireland shoulder it all alone?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The terrorists who had killed Mary and the twins had been trained and armed in Libya. And there was England\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s filt\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 hy hand in the whole mess \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0 
 eight hundred years of cynical oppression \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0 \hich\f0  \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Ireland, the guilty conscience of the English ruling class.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      As this change became fixed in its purpose, John saw an astonishing alteration of his appearance. The old almost plum\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
p self went stringing down to a slender, nervous man, who avoided old friends, refused to answer the telephone and ignored appointments. People made allowances at first \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0 \hich\f0  \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
The awful shock of such a tragedy\'85\'94\loch\f0  The foundation that had sent him to Ireland gav\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
 him an unrequested extension on the project with a polite letter asking if he wanted to turn it over to another researcher. The school extended his leave of absence. Max Dunn, who managed the family pharmacy, took over more of the business decisions and 
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 t\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 old John not to concern himself with anything except getting his life back in order.
