\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 er closed to them.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      One of the soldiers above him ventured: \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Colonel, is it a bad sickness they have over there?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 So I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ve been told,\'94\loch\f0  the colonel said. He lowered his glasses, scanned the emplacement, fixing his gaze finally on a tall sergeant w
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 ho stood somewhat apart. \'93\loch\f0 Get some shelters up, Sergeant. And you\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 re to look sharp. Only the medics are to enter that place and no one\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s to leave.
\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  \'93\loch\f0 We\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ll not let so much as a fox through, sir.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Turning away, the colonel took long-legged strides down \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 the slope to a jeep waiting on the narrow track below the emplacement.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      As one, the soldiers he had left behind looked across at Achill, the island of the eagles, which no longer were there. It was a brooding landscape in the rain, a speckling of white\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
 rocks and buildings against the greens. The few roads cut gray ledges around the hills and the ocean was a deeper gray below. Slievemore and Croaghaun thrust almost into the clouds toward Achill Head\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s outer cliffs. It was a place turned in upon itself a\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 n\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
d the men looking across at the island could feel the simmering mood of the land. Generations of men and women had brooded passionately there on the wrongs done to Ireland. No Irishman could fail to sense that thing smoldering there, the sullen hopes of a
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 l\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 l those who had perished for \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 The Irish Dream.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ll be a scurrying-around time for the priests,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  the sergeant said, then: \'93\loch\f0 Now, men, you heard the colonel. Shouldn\hich\f0 
\rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 t we be raising some shelters?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Far below this position and at the Achill end o\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 f the bridge where the town street became the highroad to the island\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s interior, Mulvaney\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s Saloon Bar had begun to collect a crowd of local residents and a few tourists. They hunched against the rain, hurrying from cars and bicycles into the bar\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s steamy\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
interior with its thick smells of wet wool and beer. Mulvaney\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s, a two-story whitewashed building with slate roof and three massive chimneys, was one of the island\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s natural assembly points. It was soon crowded with men talking too loudly, their faces ang\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 r\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 y, their gestures abrupt and latent with violence.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      A small Garda patrol car pulled up outside, bringing a lull in the conversations as the word of it was spread through the bar. Denis Flynn, the local Garda, emerged from the car. Flynn, a small blond 
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 man with light blue eyes and a boyish face, appeared pale and trembling. Way was made for him as he entered the bar, pressed through the crowd to the western end and climbed onto a chair.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      In the expectant silence, Flynn\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s voice was a thin tenor, which\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0  broke in unexpected places. \'93\loch\f0 We\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 
ve been quarantined,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  he said. \'93\loch\f0 They\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 re sending medical teams by helicopter. No one is to enter or leave the island except the medical people and officials.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      In the sudden babble of shouted questions, Flynn raised his \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 voice to demand silence, then: \'93\loch\f0 We\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 ll just have to be patient. Everything\hich\f0 
\rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s being done that can be done.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Mulvaney, a soft giant of a man with a bald head as shiny as his polished bar, thrust his way through the crowd to stand below Flynn. Hooking a t\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 humb over his shoulder, Mulvaney said: 
\'93\loch\f0 It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s my Molly sick back there and only the one doctor. I want to know what it is.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 m only the Garda,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Flynn said. \'93\loch\f0 It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s the medical men will have to answer that.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Mulvaney glanced out the windows beyond \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
Flynn, looking toward Knockmore and the village of Droega, which lay hidden beyond the hills in the hollow that protected it from the worst of the Atlantic gales. His brother, Francis, had called from there not ten minutes ago to report another death, his
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 voice full of the tears as he spoke.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      Turning a hard stare up at Flynn, Mulvaney said: \'93\loch\f0 Your womenfolk are living safe beyond Mulrany. You can take the official view. But it\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 
s my sister-in-law, Shaneen, died this morning.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      A man back in the press \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 of people shouted: \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 And my Katie has the sickness! We want answers, Flynn, and we want them now!\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ve told you what I know,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Flynn said. \'93\loch\f0 That\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s all I can do.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 What\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s this about officials coming?\'94\loch\f0  Mulvaney demanded.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 From the Health Offic\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 e in Dublin.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Why do they have soldiers barring our way?\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  someone else demanded. \'93\loch\f0 They\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ve even guns up on Corraun!\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 There\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s no need to create a panic,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Flynn said. \'93\loch\f0 But it\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s a serious matter.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Then why do we not hear it on the wireless?\'94\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 Mulvaney asked.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 Haven\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t I said we don\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 t want a panic?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s the plague, isn\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 t it?\'94\loch\f0  Mulvaney asked.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      An abrupt silence settled over the room. A small dark man with pinched features, standing at Flynn\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s right, cleared his throat.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 There\hich\f0 \rquote \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 s our own boats,\'94\loch\f0  the man said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 There\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ll be none of that, Martin!\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Flynn snapped, glaring down at the speaker. \'93\loch\f0 The navy\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 
ll be here in a few minutes to collect your boats. My orders are to prevent your leaving Achill\'85\loch\f0 \hich\f0  using what force necessary.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0    \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0   His voice hoarse, Mulvaney asked: \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Are all of our womenfolk to die then? Nineteen dead since yesterday and only the women and girls. Why is that, Denis?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 The doctors will find the answer,\'94\loch\f0  Flynn said. He jumped down off the chair, steadying himself\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
 against Mulvaney, but not looking the man in the eye. Flynn\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s own superintendent had voiced that same fear less than an hour earlier, speaking with gentle firmness over the telephone.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 If all the women die there it could be very bad, Denis. And there\loch\af0\dbch\af11\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s talk it was done deliberately. You\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 
re not to speak of that now!\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Deliberate? By the Ulstermen or the British?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 ll not discuss it, Denis. I speak only to impress you with the gravity of our situation. You there inside the quarantine will be\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
 alone for a bit to represent authority. We depend on you.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Will I get no help then?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 Some soldiers are being asked to volunteer, but they\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ll not be along until the afternoon.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 I didn\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 t volunteer, sir.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 But you swore an oath to do y\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 our duty and that\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s what I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 m asking of you now!\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      As he pressed his way out of Mulvaney\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s, ignoring the questions still being shouted at him, Flynn recalled that telephone conversation. There had been more orders and things he must do now.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The rai\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 n had turned to a light mist as he emerged from the bar. He got into his car, not looking at the angry faces peering at him from Mulvaney\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s. Starting the motor, he turned around and drove slowly down to the concrete apron overlooking Achill Sound and the \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 f\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
ishboats anchored there. He could see a fast patrol boat spreading a wide bow wave as it sped down from the Bulls Mouth. It appeared to be no more than five minutes away, for which he was thankful. He parked on the concrete and took his shotgun from its r
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 a\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 ck, feeling strange with the weapon in his hands. The superintendent had been firm with his instructions.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 I want you on armed watch, Denis, until they pick up those small boats. I want it understood that you\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ll use your weapon if necessary.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Fly\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
nn stared bleakly across the water at the approaching patrol boat. Seabirds were wheeling and calling over the strand. He inhaled the familiar salt odors, the smell of the seaweeds and the pungency of fish. How many times had he looked on this scene and n
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 ver thought it strange? Flynn wondered. Now, though\'85\loch\f0  the differences sent a shuddering through his thin body. The thing he had wanted to say back at Mulvaney\hich\f0 \rquote 
\loch\f0 s, the thing that had filled his throat with sourness, stood uppermost in his mind.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      But his s\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 uperintendent had been adamant on the need for secrecy. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
A great many women are sure to die, perhaps all on the island. We count on you to keep the peace until help arrives. There must be no panic, no mobs. You must be firm in keeping order.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 I shoul\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 d\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ve told them,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Flynn muttered to himself. \'93\loch\f0 They should be bringing in the priests. It\hich\f0 
\rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s sure nothing else will help them now.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      He stared out at the moored fishboats, feeling a deep loneliness and a sense of inadequacy.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 Lord help us now in the \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 hour of our need,\'94\loch\f0  he whispered.
