\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Without any particular pride, John thought his lab in the basement of the Ballard house a marvel of ingenuity. The centrifuge that he had improvised out \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
of tire-balancing equipment had cost less than a thousand dollars. His freezer was stock home bar equipment turned on its back and with a calibrated thermostat added. It was accurate to within one degree Centigrade. He had improvised peristaltic pumps fro
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 m\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
 scuba equipment. His cell disrupter was adapted from a used yachting sonar. The electron microscope, a dual-stage thirty Angstrom resolution ISI model, cost him the most time and considerable money. It was provided as a consignment-theft item by the San 
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 F\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 rancisco underworld at a cost of twenty-five thousand dollars.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      And so it went with the entire lab. He fashioned the negative-pressure research rooms out of plywood and plastic film. The airlock was sealed by two small boat hatches, which forced him to\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
 crawl into and out of the rooms. It was the only major inconvenience.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Before the lab was completed, John was at work with his computer, setting up the full-color graphics of the molecular models upon which he would center his attention. In parallel \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
computer storage circuits, he filed away everything he could ferret out about the ways existing drugs functioned in the body. He paid particular attention to known data on enzymes and specific DNA receptors.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      It gratified him to discover that many of t\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 he most important requirements for his molecular maps were available in \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 canned\'94\loch\f0  form \hich\f0 \endash 
\loch\f0  on computer discs or in storage programs that could be bought or stolen. By the time the lab was completed he had his computer loaded with the elemental building block\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 s\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  of his project.

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
     There was a hypnotic fascination in sitting before the cathode display, watching the double spirals of the primal helix turn and twist at his command. The red, green, purple and yellow lines took on a life of their own. His mind and t
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
he display fell into a kind of unified space within which it was difficult to separate which was in his mind and which in the screen. It seemed at times as if his hands on the computer controls created the images in his head, or the image would be in his 
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 h\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 ead and then appear as if miraculously on the screen. There were moments when he thought he was actually speaking in the language of the genetic code, talking to specific sites on DNA molecules.

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      During these periods, the actual flow of time vanished f\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
rom his consciousness. On one occasion, he crawled from the airlock hatch, staggered to his feet and found it just dawn outside. Investigation revealed that he had been working steadily for thirty-seven hours with only an occasional sip of water. He was a
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 c\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 hingly hungry and his trembling hands could not even deal with solid food until he drank almost a full quart of milk.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The structure he needed to see and understand was slowly revealing itself, though, both on the screen and in the computer-monitored o\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
utputs of his lab. He knew it was only a matter of time until he fitted the proper molecular key into the biological lock. The answers were here in the lab and in his head. They merely had to be opened out into their own reality. The nucleotide sequences 
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 o\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 f the DNA encoded all of the genetic information for every biological function. It was a code-breaking problem.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Without the computer he would have been lost. At any given moment he might be working with four thousand to twenty thousand genes. The mapp\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
ed arrangements of these genes and the DNA codes within them could project into more than a million genes. He did not need all of those genes, though \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0  only the key ones whose coding lay in the particular nucleotide sequences.

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      By disruption, by enzyme\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  fractionating and temperature-controlled separation with collimators and centrifuge, he sought out the bits and pieces that his mind/computer images told him were there.

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Before long, he was fashioning ribosomal RNAs and messenger RNAs from his own DN\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
A templates, selecting and discarding, seeking out the control sites in the genomes. These and the regulatory proteins were his first targets.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Some two months into the project, John realized he would need a special supply of natural DNA for the polyme\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
rization cycle. The DNA had to be biologically active and it had to carry the templates he required. There was no escaping the fact that the DNA material transferred in pairs, one of each pair being a mirror of its opposite number.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      His head ached with\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0  thinking about the problem, but he could not avoid the immediate necessity. It would risk exposure. It was dangerous\'85\loch\f0  but he could see no alternative.

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      A session with his forging kit gave him a passable identification as a John Vicenti, M.D., Public H\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
ealth Service. He had bought a small hand press early in fitting out the equipment for his project. This now produced some quite adequate letterheads. On these he typed letters of authorization, scrawling big signatures of officials at the bottoms. He bou
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 g\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
ht a dark wig, toned his skin olive and all the while kept watch through the newspapers for a school immunization date. It came within the week, announcement of an immunization program in West Seattle Junior High School for the following Monday.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Wear\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
ing a white jacket with stethoscope protruding from a side pocket and a name tag on his lapel identifying him as John Vicenti, M.D., he showed up early at the school. It was a cold winter morning and the halls were crowded with students bundled into heavy
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
jackets. He moved through the shouting, jabbering throng without attracting more than casual notice. In his left hand he carried a carefully arranged wooden kit box containing racks of sterile slides and covers and all of the neatly assembled tools for bl
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 o\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 od sampling. In his left hand was the briefcase with his authorizations.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      He bustled officiously into the school nurse\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s office, noting her name on the door: \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Jeanette Blanquie.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Hi,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  he said, all innocence. \'93\loch\f0 I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 m Doctor Vicenti. Where do I set up\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 ?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Set up?\'94\loch\f0 
 Nurse Blanquie was a slender blond young woman with a permanently harried expression. She stood behind a long table upon which the immunization kits were set out in orderly rows. There was an empty chair at the far end of the table with t
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 wo stacks of forms in front of it. The wall behind her displayed a calendar and two bowdlerized anatomical charts, one labeled \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 male,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  the other \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 female.
\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 For the blood samples,\'94\loch\f0  he said. He put his wooden box and briefcase on the table and showed he\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
r his identification and authorizations. Nurse Blanquie merely glanced at them while her expression became even more harried.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Blood samples,\'94\loch\f0  she muttered.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 We\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 re supposed to get them right along with your immunization program to minimize the up\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 set of school routine,\'94\loch\f0  he explained.

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 I was supposed to have two clinical technicians here this morning to help me,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  she said. \'93\loch\f0 
One of them just called in sick and the other one has some kind of emergency at Good Samaritan. Now you. This is all I nee\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 d. What are your samples for?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 We\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 re doing a genetic typing nationally to see if we can identify correlations with certain diseases and immunities. I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
m supposed to use your ID numbers, no names. All I need in addition is whether the sample is from ma\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 le or female.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      Her voice sounded tired. \'93\loch\f0 Doctor Vicenti, nobody\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s told me a thing.\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  She gestured at the table. \'93\loch\f0 And I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
\hich\f0 m supposed to process two hundred and sixteen students today, more tomorrow.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      He gritted his teeth. \'93\loch\f0 Damn! That\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s their second s\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 lip-up in two weeks! Somebody in that office should be fired.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Nurse Blanquie shook her head in sympathy.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      He said: \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Well, what can I do to help you? Could we get a student in to handle the paperwork?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ve already asked for one,\'94\loch\f0  she said. \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 She looked at the table in front of her. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
Could you set up here beside me? What kind of samples will you take?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      He opened the kit box, displaying the ranked slides, the swabs and alcohol, lancets, everything neat.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Oh,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  she said. \'93\loch\f0 Well, that shou\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 ldn\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 
t delay us much, Doctor. I guess between the two of us we can handle it.\'94
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      When he returned to Ballard that evening, \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Doctor Vicenti\'94\loch\f0  had two hundred and eleven blood samples, each with a tiny pinch of skin cells deftly included.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      There will b\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 e specific differences, he told himself as he removed his disguise in the bathroom, which still smelled of stale tobacco. The genetic information for every biological function 
\hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0  including whether the person is male or female. There is a pattern here into \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 w\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 hich I can lock a virulent destroyer.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The positive intermolding effect of the double helix chains, each side able to reproduce its opposite number, his clues lay in there. In the peptide bonds, perhaps, and in the singular tails that trailed out of th
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 e helix.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      He took the samples down to his lab. The answers had to be in here, he assured himself. It was in the DNA patterns. Had to be. When a bacterial virus infected a bacterium, it was the virus\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s DNA, not its protein, that entered the bacterial ce\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 ll. Here was the messenger he needed to make John O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 Neill\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s revenge heard everywhere.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The technique for testing his results already had been worked out. It would be elegant in the extreme. He would require short-lived virus-mediated bacterial forms, b\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
acteria that would induce visible effects in a selected population. The effects would have to be identifiable and visible, not fatal but important enough to cause comment. The test bacilli would have to be self-lethal. They would have to vanish of themsel
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 v\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 es.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
     These requirements, which might have daunted a major research center, did not even give him pause. He had a feeling of invincibility. It was only one step in his project. When he had the key to this lock, when he had assured himself of its identit
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 y, then he could start shaping the key into its more virulent form.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      And then the message could be sent.
