\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      As President Prescott replaced the receiver on his telephone, he reflected on the conversation with Bergen. Quite satisfactory. Yes, quite well done on both s\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
ides. Of course, Bergen would be calling in the counter he\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 d just given. There would be a quid pro quo sometime. Well, that could be an advantage, too. Bergen was too good a politician to ask for something he knew he couldn
\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t get.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Charles Turkwood, th\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 e President\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s personal aide and confidant, stood just across the desk from where Prescott sat. The Oval Office was very quiet, not even the sound of someone typing in one of the outer offices. That was one of the things that had happened \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0 
 not as much typ\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 i\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 ng. More was being done in direct telephone conversation, as just now with Bergen.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Turkwood was a short, saturnine man with close-cropped black hair. Widely set cold black eyes looked out over a rather short nose. The lips were thick, chin wide and bl\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
unt. He knew himself for an ugly man, but power had its compensations. He often thought of himself as a perfect counterpoint to Prescott\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s tall, gray-haired dignity. Adam Prescott had the look of a kindly and benevolent soap opera grandfather. His voice w\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 a\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 s a gentle baritone.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 He went for it, eh?\'94\loch\f0  Turkwood asked, deciphering the half of the telephone conversation he had heard.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Prescott did not answer. He bent over the desk reading a copy of one of the Madman\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s letters. Turkwood, perfectly capable \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
of reading upside down, glanced at what had caught the President\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s attention. Ah, yes \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0  O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 Neill\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s atomic warning:
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 You will think of using atomic sterilization upon the targets of my revenge. Don\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t do it. I will turn against you if you do. The plague \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
must run its course in Ireland, Great Britain and Libya. I want the men to survive and to know what it was I did to them. You will be permitted to quarantine them, nothing more. Send their nationals home \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0 
 all of them. Let them stew there. If you fail to \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 xpel so much as a babe in arms who belongs in one of those nations by reason of nationality or birth, you will feel my anger.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 Neill said it plainly enough, Turkwood thought.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The President finished reading, but remained silent, staring out the \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 window toward the Washington Monument.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      It was one of the President\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s more disconcerting habits, maintaining a long silence after a statement or a question by a subordinate. It was assumed during such periods that the President was thinking, which he o\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
ften was. But a silence unduly prolonged allowed considerable time for an underling to speculate about what the President might be thinking. Even unimaginative people can imagine very dark things under such conditions.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Of all his close associates, onl\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 y Charlie Turkwood guessed that this was a deliberate mannerism, cultivated for precisely the effect it achieved.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 He went for it,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Prescott said finally, swiveling to face Turkwood. \'93\loch\f0 We\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 ll have to watch carefully now. It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s entirely a United Nations t\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 hing and we\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 re just going along for the ride.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 What\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ll he want in return?\'94\loch\f0  Turkwood asked.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 In due time,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Prescott said. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 All in due time, Charlie.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 Sir, did the secretary-general try to bring up the question of who has ultimate control ov\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 er Barrier Command?\'94\loch\f0  Turkwood asked.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 Not a word. Bergen understands that we handle only one hot potato at a time whenever that\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s possible.\'94
