\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The metal bed of the lorry was chilling beneath John\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s bare skin. He curled himself into a tight ball, his arms hugged around his chest, but \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 the lorry\hich\f0 \rquote 
\loch\f0 s movement jostled him and a cold wind blew through the canvas cover over the bed. They had stripped him bare on the float at Kinsale, parceling out his clothes and the contents of his pack, arguing over who would get the six French chocolate ba
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 r\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 s.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Kevin O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 Donnell had appeared uninterested in all of this, but he had kept the money and the Belgian pistol.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 Why\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 re you doing this?\'94\loch\f0  John had demanded.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 Because we\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 re kindly men,\'94\loch\f0  Kevin O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 Donnell had said. \'93\loch\f0 We kill anyone we catch within 
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 five hundred meters of the shore.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Even if we come in from the sea?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Well, me and the boys were disappointed in you, Yank. We were expecting some folks from another coffin ship, maybe a pretty woman or two.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      One of the men stripping John s\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 aid: \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Not many women surviving the trip anymore.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      They finished with him, removing even his shoes and socks. He stood, hugging himself, bare and shivering on the cold float.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 Just be happy we\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 re sparing you, Yank,\'94\loch\f0  Kevin O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 Donnell had said. \'93\loch\f0 Up y\loch\af0\dbch\af11\hich\f0 \rquote 
\loch\f0  go, Yank. Into the lorry with him, boys. And this time, bring some of the good stuff back wi\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0  you.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Three guards had entered the back of the lorry with John. He caught the name of only one, Muiris Cohn, a small man with a face that appeared compress\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
ed from top to bottom, the closely set eyes too near the nose, the nose too close to the mouth and the chin almost touching his lower lip.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      While the three guards occupied a bench on one side, John was forced to stay on the chilled bed. When he complai\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 ned of the cold, Cohn nudged him roughly with a heavy boot and said: \'93
\loch\f0 Now, y\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0  heard Kevin! You\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 re alive and it\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s more than you deserve.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      To John, the trip drew itself out into an interminable frigid torture, which he endured by promising himself he wo\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
uld live and, if his story was believed, he would work his way into whatever the Irish were doing to solve the plague problem. There, he would sabotage that effort.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The lorry went first up a steep hill, rolling John toward the back. His captors dragge\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 d him forward again, wedging him near their feet.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Which way we going?\'94\loch\f0  one of them asked the others.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 I heard them say the road through Belgooly is safest,\'94\loch\f0  Cohn said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 That means they\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ve restored Fivemilebridge,\'94\loch\f0  the questioner said. He wa\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 s silent for a moment, then: \'93\loch\f0 
How long\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ll we be stopping in Cork?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Now, Gilly,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Cohn said, \'93\loch\f0 the times you\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ve made this trip and you still asking such a question!\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 ve a thirst the River Lee itself and it running full in the spring could not we\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 t,\'94\loch\f0  the questioner said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 And you\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ll have to wait until we rid ourselves of this lout,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Cohn said. He kicked John in the shoulder. \'93\loch\f0 We\hich\f0 \rquote 
\loch\f0 ll get as wet as the seas themselves on the way back. It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s either that or answer to Kevin himself, which I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 ll not be\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
 doing, him in the mad mood as you could see.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      John, sensing a faint warmth from his captors\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0  feet, wriggled closer, but Cohn felt the movement in the darkness and thrust him away with one foot, sneering: \'93\loch\f0 
Keep your stinking self away from us, Yank. I\loch\af0\dbch\af11\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ll be bathing for a week just to get the smell of you off me feet.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      John found himself wedged against a metal support post for the bench on his side of the lorry\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s bed. The sharp edge of the post cut into his back, but it was a different pain from th
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 e cold. He focused on this new pain, clinging to it. The darkness, the cold, the pain began to work on him. He had thought O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
Neill safely buried deep within, obscured and hidden away forever. But his nakedness, the dark and cold bed of the lorry, these we\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 r\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
e not a place he had ever imagined. He could feel a terrible inner warfare waiting to occur. And he began to hear the lunatic sound of that inner voice \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0  John Roe O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 Neill clamoring for his revenge.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 You\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ll have it,\'94\loch\f0  he muttered.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The sound of his \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 voice was almost covered by the grinding rumble of the lorry as it climbed a hill. Cohn heard him, though, and asked:
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 Did y\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0  say something, Yank?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      When John did not answer, Cohn kicked him. \'93\loch\f0 I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ll have an answer from you, damn your evil soul!\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0   \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0    \'93\loch\f0 It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s cold,\'94\loch\f0  John said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 Ahhh, that\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s fine now,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Cohn said. \'93\loch\f0 We wouldn\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 t want you to enter our world comfortable like.\'94

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Cohn\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s companions laughed.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s the way we all enter Ireland, y\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0  know,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Cohn said. \'93\loch\f0 Naked as plucked chickens and the
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 m ready for the pot. You\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 ve no mind for the pot you\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 re in now, you Yankee devil.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      They fell silent then and John lapsed back into the arena of his inner war. He could feel the presence of O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 Neill. It was a single eye like a beam of light glaring from \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
\hich\f0 within his head. No warmth in it. Cold\'85\loch\f0 \hich\f0  cold\'85\loch\f0  as cold as the metal upon which his body lay.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The lorry rumbled across a wooden bridge and the sound of the tires against the planks was a drumbeat in John\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s head. He could sense O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 Neill trying to emerge a
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 nd this terrified him. O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 Neill did not belong here! O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 Neill would scream. The three guards would enjoy that.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Lights!
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      He sensed lights out the open rear of the lorry and this restored him somewhat. He realized that his eyes were tightly closed and\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 , slowly, he opened them. O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
Neill sank back into obscurity.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The lights were on both sides of the lorry \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0  a well-lighted city street. He could hear people shouting. It was a drunken sound. There was a gunshot, then high-pitched laughter. He tried to si
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 t up, but Cohn pushed him back with a foot.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Painted like hussies,\'94\loch\f0  one of the other guards said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      John felt a crouching sensation. Had some of the women survived? That high-pitched laughter. Had his plague failed?
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Would they were hussies,\'94\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Cohn said. \'93\loch\f0 I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 d even welcome old Bella Cohen and the Monto, the saucy darlin
\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s beckoning us with their skirts lifted.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 d be better than this,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  the other guard said. \'93\loch\f0 Men with men! It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 
s against the Commandments, Muiris!\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s all they have, G\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 illy,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Cohn said. \'93\loch\f0 They haven\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 
t our opportunities to get a warm woman into bed.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s the buryin\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0  of \hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 em afterwards I don\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 t like,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
 the other guard said. \'93\loch\f0 Why didn\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t the sanctuaries save \hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 em, Muiris?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 Ohhhh, it\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s a terrible, virulent thing, this\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0  plague. A short life. Better it be merry, as the poet said.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ll never lay with a man!\'94\loch\f0  Gilly said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Save that for the time when the coffin ships come no more, Gilly.\'94\loch\f0  Cohn slid back along the bench past John and peered out the rear of the lor\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
ry. \'93\loch\f0 Isn\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 t it a shame, the fine city of Cork come to this!\'94\loch\f0  He returned to the others.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Did you hear that the English queen died?\'94\loch\f0  Gilly asked.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Good riddance! Best see an end to the House of Windsor!\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The lorry made a slow, tight turn to th\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 e left and the driver shifted down for a hill. The guards lapsed into silence.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      John kept his eyes open, watching the shadows on the canvas overhead. The lorry picked up speed along smooth paving.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 The N-Twenty-five\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s mostly clean now,\'94\loch\f0  Cohn said.\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0  \'93\loch\f0 We\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
ll be in Youghal soon enough. Then it\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s back to the bright lights, eh, Gilly?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 I think it was the devil kissed your mother,\'94\loch\f0  Gilly said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      Cohn laughed. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 And maybe he did a bit more, eh?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Have you the cloven hoof, Muiris?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 I know \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 how to survive in these times, Gilly. You just be remembering that. Kevin and me, we know the ways that\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 re needed now.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Gilly did not answer.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      In spite of the pain and the cold, John felt himself dozing. It had been a long, tiring time at the sail\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 boat\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s tiller and then the shock of his reception. His eyes closed. He opened them quickly, willing them to stay open despite fatigue. He did not want O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 Neill to return.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      They passed an occasional vehicle going the other way and the lights through the \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
canvas cover showed the guards with their eyes closed. Once, a car overtook them moving very fast, its lights flashing into the lorry\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s rear, then darkness. The car\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s motor whined in very high revolutions.

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 From Dublin,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Cohn said. \'93\loch\f0 I saw the flag on \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 its fender.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 He was doing at least two hundred,\'94\loch\f0  Gilly said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 All of that,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Cohn said. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 They move very fast, do our superiors.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Three times the lorry slowed to a lurching crawl over rough ground before returning to the smooth pavement. The \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 fourth time it slowed, Cohn said the one word: \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
Youghal.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ll be glad to load and turn around,\'94\loch\f0  Gilly said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 And be shut of this baggage,\'94\loch\f0  Cohn said, nudging John with a foot.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      John felt them making a sweeping turn to the left, then low gea\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 rs for about five minutes. They came to a jerking stop and someone up front shouted: \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Get him out!
\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      Cohn leaped over the tailgate and there was the sound of his feet on gravel. Presently, Cohn said: \'93\loch\f0 All right. Let\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s have him.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The two guards rem\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 aining with John had to help him to his feet. His voice not unkind, Gilly said: \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Out you go, Yank. Mind the gravel on your feet.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      John let himself down over the tailgate, moving stiffly, his muscles cramped with the cold and inactivity. Cohn took his \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
