\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\dbch\af11\insrsid3359690 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Kate O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
Gara sat at the little wall desk in their new quarters writing in her diary the things she could not say to Stephen. She knew it was a bit after 10:30 A.M. because she had just heard Moone Colum and Hugh Stil\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
es come on guard duty outside there in the castle courtyard, which, she thought, must be almost completely bricked in and covered over by now. The daylight was much dimmer than when they had been moved here.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      She wrote in the diary:
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93}{\i\dbch\af11\insrsid3359690 \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 I do not like\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  Adrian Peard. He enjoys his authority too much.}{\dbch\af11\insrsid3359690 \loch\af0\dbch\af11\hich\f0 \'94

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      In all fairness, she knew why Stephen admired the man so much. No denying Peard\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s brilliance, but he demanded this recognition at every turn. There was something lacking in him, she thought. Peard did \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 not project Stephen\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s solid reliability.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      }{\i\dbch\af11\insrsid3359690 \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 m being ungrateful}{\dbch\af11\insrsid3359690 \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 .
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Everything done here was part of a design to hold the plague at bay for one lone woman \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0  herself. Nothing was being spared, so they assured her, to keep her happy in this protracted i
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
solation. Only eleven days after Stephen had almost physically forced her into the pressure tank, a great mob of men had come with a lorry and cranes and big machines. By nightfall they had been ready to move the tank entire with Stephen and herself in it
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
like two beans rattling in a pot. There had been soldiers all around, armored vehicles and motorcycles and guns. The air pumps and a great diesel generator had been carried on the lorry with the tank. The noise of them so close had alarmed her and she had
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 clung to Stephen.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 What if the tank breaks?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s steel and very strong, love.\'94\loch\f0 
 Her ear against his chest, she could hear his voice rumbling there and the strong steady beat of his heart. That, more than the words, had calmed her.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      She had p\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
eered through the ports once and seen the lights of a city burning in the night far off across the fields. There had been fires on a distant hill as they drove down into a valley and, once, protracted gunfire stopped the convoy beside a bridge with dark w
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 a\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 ter flowing nearby in the starlight. She had huddled against Stephen until the lorry once more began to move.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      They had arrived finally at this courtyard, it illuminated by brilliant lights up high on the inner walls. Through the ports, Kate had glimps\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
ed stones and bricks piled all around, stacks of cement in sacks. There had been the crackling blue of welders and men working over large sheets of steel.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 They\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 re building us bigger quarters, love,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Stephen had explained. \'93\loch\f0 The airlock end of this tan\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
k will be fitted into the other quarters.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Will it be safe?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      No mistaking the source of her anxiety. The stories of women dying \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0  on the radio and relayed by the men outside \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0  had filled her with terror.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 Adrian will sterilize the place and\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0  everything in it,\'94\loch\f0  Stephen had reassured her.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Still, she had been reluctant to crawl out the airlock into the other rooms when the workmen had finished there. Stephen had pointed out that the new chamber contained a television and a private room for 
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 the toilet, and it even had a bath.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      To Kate, the toilet facilities had been the ugliest part of living in the smaller tank. Never mind her training as a nurse and all the understanding of bodily functions. The little tank had only this pressure-operat
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
ed bowl for a toilet and it right out in the open opposite a port. Wastes went out through a pipe into a sterile container designed originally to capture specimens for medical examination. She had forced Stephen to turn his back while she used this conven
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 i\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 ence, but anyone could look in from outside\'85\loch\f0  although she had to admit she had never seen a face at the port while she was on the damned toilet.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      And there was the smell. Within a day, the confined quarters had taken on the stench of a latrine.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Ca\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 nned food was her other complaint.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Cold canned food!\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Those three words uttered with revulsion had grated on Stephen. She had known this but could not stop herself from saying them.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      And the water in sterile bottles! No taste to it at all.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
    The new quarters had vertical walls and a flat ceiling of steel. There was even brown-and-white lino on the floor and two electric burners on a bench beside a small pressure sink. Nothing near as grand as the kitchen in Peard\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s cottage, but the food c\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 o\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
uld be heated. It all continued to come from cans, though. And the water, the tasteless water in sterile bottles! Although now they could get an occasional bottle of Guinness if it had been made before the plague.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      They still slept in the original tank\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 , but now it was on a big mattress left sterile in the new chamber. It sagged a bit toward the middle because of the tank\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s curvature, this in spite of resting on a big sheet of plywood supported at the middle by wooden blocks. The blocks had a disturbing\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 tendency to bounce and drum when she and Stephen made love.

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 We\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 re animals in a zoo!\'94\loch\f0  she complained, thinking about the men outside hearing that noise.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 But you\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 re alive, Kate!\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      She could not explain why this terrified her. It should have b\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 een reassuring.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 m alive.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      But the terrible news relayed from outside, and even some of it now seen on the telly, only made her continued existence more alarming. She felt fragile and subject to the awful whims of a malignant fate.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      In her di\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 ary, she had drawn a crude map and plotted on it the plague\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s inexorable spread \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0 
 Brittany, North Africa, Sicily, the toe of Italy, then Rome itself, the citadel of her faith. On her map, she blotted out each new plague place with ink and felt as she did \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 t\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
his that she removed these regions from her world. The plague spots were like the places marked on antique maps \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0 \hich\f0  Terra Incognita. They would have to be rediscovered\'85\loch\f0  if anyone survived.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      She knew she was not the only woman left alive in Ireland. There\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
 was talk outside that she could overhear and they answered her questions when she asked. There were women isolated in the old mines near Mountmellick and near Castleblayney. Another group of women was said to be in a great house on its own land near Clon
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 m\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 el with a madman named Brann McCrae. Rumors and reports spoke of tiny groups here and there throughout the land, each protected by desperate men.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Her own position, though, was unique.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      In his own cold-blooded way, Peard had let her know this as an\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  eavesdropper while he discussed the situation with Stephen.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Most of the other women are sure to go as their men are contaminated in the search for food.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      She had stood at a port, looking out at Peard while he spoke to Stephen by telephone. Pear\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
d was a bitter-faced little dynamo, no more than a meter and a half tall, with frigid blue eyes and a thin-lipped mouth that Kate had never seen smile. He had straw-colored hair, which he kept close-cropped or shaved off entirely, as did many of the men s
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 h\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 e saw through the ports. Peard\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s skin was tanned and the brow heavily creased by frown wrinkles.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 Can\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 t we do anything for those women?\'94\loch\f0  Stephen had asked.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 We\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 re providing sterilized food, but the men are all suspicious and won\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t accept our medi\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
cal advice nor anything else. We thought of taking some of them by force, but that would be fatal for the women. Best leave things as they are and hope.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 What about the women being sent back from overseas?\'94\loch\f0  Stephen had asked.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 Not many of them g\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 etting here alive. Those who do\'85\'94\loch\f0  Peard\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s features had grown glowering and thoughtful \'93
\loch\f0 . . . well, we tried isolating some of them, to no avail. And the Beach Boys control all the coast. They aren\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t cooperating. We\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ve had to go along or risk a civil war\'85\loch\f0  
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 w\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 hich we may do yet, although Fin says\'85\'94\loch\f0  Peard had shook his head silently, not revealing what Fin had said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Fin, she knew, would be Fintan Doheny, a man of power in the high councils.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 What about England?\'94\loch\f0  Stephen\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s voice had sounded beaten down,\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  hopeless.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 Worse than here, so we\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 
re told. It spread faster there for some reason. The Welsh say they have some women in a coal mine, but the problem of food is terrible. And the water\'85\loch\f0  Some Scots have thirty-two women isolated in Stirring Castle, bu
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 t there\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s violence in Edinburgh and mobs. Last we heard, the people at the castle were starving and some religious madman with a mob at their gates.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 Surely, we\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ll have an answer to the plague before all the women die,\'94\loch\f0  Stephen had protested.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 W\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 e\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 re working on it. Rest assured of that.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Peard\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s words, uttered as they were in his coldly impersonal way, had given her no reassurance at all.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      She had begun to cry, deep racking sobs. Her poor mother dead! And not even a funeral nor a priest t\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
o pray over her. All the women of Cork gone excepting herself. And what was she here in this room of steel? A guinea pig! She could hear it in Peard\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s voice, see it in his manner. He thought of her as an easily available test subject!
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      She longed for M\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 aggie to talk to, a woman friend to understand and speak the common language of their concerns. But Maggie was gone with the rest.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Hearing her sobs, Stephen had broken off the conversation with Peard. His arms around her helped some, but the sobs died\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  off only when she grew too tired and lost in her misery to continue them.

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 I want us to be married,\'94\loch\f0  she whispered finally.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 I know, love. I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 ve asked them to bring a priest. They\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 re trying.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Seated at the little desk against the cold steel \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 wall, Kate wrote in her diary: \'93\loch\f0 When will they bring a priest? It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 
s been fifteen days since Stephen asked.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      She could hear Moone Colum and Hugh Stiles arguing outside her wall. A trick of the acoustics made the desk a focal point for overhearing the w\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
ords of the two men out there. She often sat here listening to them. She liked old Moone in spite of his blasphemous attitude toward the Church. But he and Hugh kept up an argument about religion that had begun to bore her. They were at it again, she note
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 d\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 .
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 The system of birth and death has been broken, that it has,\'94\loch\f0  Moone said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      From behind her, she heard the page of a book turn and Stephen\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s whisper: \'93\loch\f0 Moone\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s off again.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      So he could hear them, too. She folded her arms on the desk and lower\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 ed her head to her arms, wishing the two men would take their argument someplace else.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      But Moone was ranting in that peculiar rasping whine of his, which Kate had come to identify as his angry sound: \'93\loch\f0 This completes the process begun by the Catholic C\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
hurch!\'94
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 Aw, you\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 re daft,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Hugh said. \'93\loch\f0 Birth, death \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0 \hich\f0  how can such a thing be broken?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 Would y\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0  grant me, Hugh, that the work of bearin\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0  children was once part of a circle, part of an endless return?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 You sound like one of them heathen In\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 dians,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Hugh protested. \'93\loch\f0 Next thing you\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 ll be tellin\hich\f0 
\rquote \loch\f0  me you\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 re the spirit of Moses himself come back to\'85\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 m just talkin\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0  about the circle of birth and death, y\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0  old idiot!\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      Stephen came up behind Kate and put a hand on her shoulder. \'93\loch\f0 They kno\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 w out there that you\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 re pregnant.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      Without lifting her head, she said: \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Make them bring a priest.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ll ask again.\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  He stroked her hair. \'93\loch\f0 Don\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t cut your hair, Kate. It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s beautiful when it\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s long this way.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Hearing a bustle of movement outsi\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 de, Kate lifted her head against his hand. She heard Peard\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s voice commanding someone to ready the small airlock.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      Stephen went to the speaker phone and keyed it. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 What is it, Adrian?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 m sending in a pistol, Stephen. We\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 re sterilizing it right \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 now.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 A pistol? In the name of heaven, why?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Fin told me to do it, in case someone tries to break in there.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Who would do that?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 We\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 d not let them!\'94\loch\f0  That was Moone Colum.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s just a precaution, Stephen,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Peard said. \'93\loch\f0 But keep\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0  it handy.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      He\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s lying, Stephen thought. But he knew if he continued to question, it would upset Kate. She was looking up at him now, fear in her eyes.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 Well, if Fin says it, I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ll do it,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Stephen said, \'93\loch\f0 but I think it\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s a damned foolishness with 
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 men like Moone and Hugh out there guarding us.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Kate\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s mouth formed a silent question.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      Stephen nodded. \'93\loch\f0 When\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 re you going to bring us that priest?\'94\loch\f0  he asked.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 We\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 re doing our best. There were so many of them killed at Maynooth and now, well,\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
 we must find one willing to come here and one we can trust, to boot.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 What do you mean trust?\'94\loch\f0  Kate demanded.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 There\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 re some strange goings-on in our world, Katie,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Peard said. \'93\loch\f0 Don\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
t you worry your pretty head, though. We\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 ll find you a priest.\loch\af0\dbch\af11\hich\f0 \'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      She hated it when Peard called her Katie. So damned condescending! But she felt so helpless in here, so dependent upon the good will of everyone out there. And such terrible things were happening.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Thank you,\'94\loch\f0  she said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Stephen and Peard b\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
egan talking about her as a patient, then. Peard said he was bringing an obstetrician to brief Stephen. Kate tuned them out. She did not like being discussed as though she were a piece of meat. She knew Stephen had wanted this briefing, though. It was his
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 loving concern about her and she was thankful for that, at least.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      When they were finished, Peard went away, but he left his phone key open and she could hear Hugh and Moone through the speaker. They were talking about the efforts to maintain a semblan\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
ce of normalcy in the land.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 There\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s talk of restoring the canals,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Hugh said. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Why? What would they carry? From where and to where?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      Moone agreed with him. \'93\loch\f0 There\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s no future in it, Hugh.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Kate put her hands over her ears.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      No future in\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  it!
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Hardly a day went by without someone outside there using those awful words in just that way. No future in it.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      She lowered her hands to her abdomen, feeling for it to begin swelling with the new life, trying to feel the actual living presence\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  there.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 We must have a future,\'94\loch\f0  she whispered.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      But Stephen had gone back to his medical books and did not hear her.
