\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Within an hour of the meeting at the lake, the road along which John walked with\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
 his new companions began to climb toward a notch at the top of the valley. It was still and hot on the macadam, the sunlight glinting off the leaves beside the road, reflecting glitter dazzles from minerals in the rock walls on both sides.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Herity loo\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 ked at the three backs ahead of him, thinking how easy it would be to eliminate them there \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0 
 one short burst from the machine pistol in his pack. Someone would hear, though. And there\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 d be the bodies for Kevin\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s people to find. Dirty son of a witch-whore,\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 that Kevin. Of all the types in Ireland now, Kevin\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s was probably the most dangerous: Creepies. No telling what they might do next. Those three up ahead, now: They were natural wanderers \hich\f0 
\endash \loch\f0  even the Yank. No place could hold them for long. They weren\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t lik\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
 the coffin-sleepers waiting just to die. That Yank might be a hater, as well, though. There was steel in his eyes. And the priest could easily become a death-drinker, a Slobber. Lucky the boy didn\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t talk. He\hich\f0 \rquote 
\loch\f0 d be a wee whiner for sure. God save us from t\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 h\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 e moaners and the psalm singers and the professional patriots!
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      John, glancing back at Herity, thought what an oddly silent lot they were: the boy who would not speak, the priest who made decisions without discussing them, and Herity back there \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0  a dan
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 gerous man sunk in a sullen remoteness from which only his dark eyes probed occasionally at the passing landscape. Something about Herity disturbed O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
Neill-Within, vexing John with unwanted flickers of other-memories, things better not recalled lest they \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 a\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
waken the screams. He looked at the priest for distraction and found a wild look there in eyes that did not flinch away. John was the first to break their locked gazes, putting down a surge of rage at this priest, this Flannery. It was easy to recognize t
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 h\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 e priest\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s type \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0 
 a man who early in life had discovered the violence and power in an absolutely arrogant belief. Oh, yes, that was this Flannery. He\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 d wrapped this belief around himself, put it on like armor\'85\loch\f0 \hich\f0  and now
\'85\loch\f0  now, his armor had been penetrated.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0     Once more, John glanced at the priest and found the man looking back at Herity.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      No help there, Priest!
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Easy to see what Flannery was doing: he was desperately engaged in repairing the wreck of his armor. His life was pouring out through the h\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
oles and he was grasping at the old arrogance, trying to fit the broken pieces in place, trying to restore the armor behind which he could stand untouched by his world while he made others dance to his whims. He was like a virgin compromised and there was
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 something furtively dirty about him.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      John looked down at the boy. Where was the mother? Probably dead. Just as dead as Mary and the twins.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      Father Michael, seeing John look at the boy, asked: \'93\loch\f0 How did you come to Ireland, Mister O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 Donnell?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      I\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 t was as though the name restored him to himself, setting up the genial pose that he knew would work best here. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Call me John.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s a good name, John,\'94\loch\f0  Father Michael said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      John heard Herity quickening his pace to catch up.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 I came to Irel\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 and\'85\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  John said, \'93\loch\f0 well, it\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s a long story.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 We\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ve all the time there is,\'94\loch\f0  Herity said from John\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s right. They were walking four abreast now up the steepening road.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      John thought a moment, then picked up his story where the warship\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s launch left h\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 im in the bay at Kinsale.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 They stripped you naked and left you to die on the road?\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Father Michael asked. \'93\loch\f0 Ahhh, those Beach Boys \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0 
 violent men and full of rage. No appreciation of man\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s goodness.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 They let him live,\'94\loch\f0  Herity said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 They tr\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 ade on our sorrows,\'94\loch\f0  Father Michael said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      The remotely unctuous tone grated on John. He asked: \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Do the men of the warships come in to Kinsale regularly?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 They send in supplies and armaments on unmanned boats, which they sink afterwards. The Beac\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
h Boys repay this by guarding our shores, preventing anyone from trying to leave.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 And what else would you have them do?\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Herity asked. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Would you send this madness into other lands? And you a man of the cloth!\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 That\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s not what I mean, Joseph H\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 erity, and you know it!\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 Then you don\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 t think our shores need guarding?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 That they do, but I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 d take no pleasure in it. And I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 d greet such as Mister O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 
Donnell with a more kindly reception than the one he describes.\'94\loch\f0  Father Michael shook his head\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0  sadly. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 The IRA come to this.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 What\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s that you say?\'94\loch\f0  John asked. He felt his heartbeat quickening. His face felt warm and flushed.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      Father Michael said: \'93\loch\f0 The Finn Sadal, our Beach Boys, is mostly the IRA. They fell so easy into this, I wonder di\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 d they not always trade on our sorrow?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 There\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s some would kill you for saying less,\'94\loch\f0  Herity said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 And you among them, Mister Herity?\'94\loch\f0  Father Michael asked. He sent a probing stare at Herity.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Aw now, Father,\'94\loch\f0  Herity said, his tone smooth \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 and placating. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 I was only giving you the caution. Watch your tongue, man.
\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The boy, who had been looking from one speaker to the other during this exchange, his face expressionless, suddenly darted off to the edge of the road. He picked up a rock the\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
re and hurled it down into the trees at the head of the lake. A cloud of rooks rifted from the trees as the rock disappeared into the greenery. The birds\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
 harsh cries filled the air as they whirled in a black spiral that threaded out into a line winging s\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 o\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 uthward across the lake.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 There\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s Ireland for you,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Father Michael said. \'93\loch\f0 Shouts and cries when we\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 
re disturbed, then off we go someplace else to wait for another disturbance.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Is there no government then?\'94\loch\f0  John asked.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 Oh, there\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s all the \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 trappings,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Father Michael said. \'93\loch\f0 But the real power\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
\hich\f0 s with the army and that means the rule of guns.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The boy returned to Father Michael\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s side where he took up his position, walking along as though he had never left there. His face was placid. John \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
wondered if the boy might be deaf\'85\loch\f0  but, no. He obeyed spoken orders.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s always been the rule of guns, I fear,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Father Michael said. \'93\loch\f0 Nothing\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s changed.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Are the Beach Boys part of the government?\'94\loch\f0  John asked. He felt O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 Neill-Within waiting fo\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 r the answer.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 They\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ve guns,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Father Michael said. \'93\loch\f0 And they\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ve men in the high councils.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      Herity said: \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Oh, some things has changed, Priest. Some things has changed very much.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\lquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 Tis a fact, I agree,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Father Michael said. \'93\loch\f0 We\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 ve gone back t\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
o the feudal times. Futile, too, if you take my meaning.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 Ah, the priest\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s a poet!\'94\loch\f0  Herity said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      John looked up as the light around them darkened abruptly. He saw that clouds had come in from the west, a dark scudding line of them carrying the h\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 int of rain.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 There\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s no democracy,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Father Michael said. \'93\loch\f0 Perhaps there never was, it being a precious jewel men steal when it\hich\f0 \rquote 
\loch\f0 \hich\f0 s left unguarded.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 But we\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ve one government in Dublin for all of Ireland,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Herity said. \'93\loch\f0 Tell me, Father Michael, isn\loch\af0\dbch\af11\hich\f0 
\rquote \loch\f0 t that something we\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ve always wanted?\'94\loch\f0  He turned a sly grin toward the priest.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s the same old bickering and jealousies,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Father Michael said. \'93\loch\f0 We\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 re still divided.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 Don\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t listen to him, Mister O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 Donnell,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Herity said. \'93\loch\f0 He\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s just a crazy old
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0  priest.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The boy scowled at Herity but only John noticed.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s a very ancient way with us,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Father Michael said, \'93\loch\f0 
part of the original Gaelic madness. We divide ourselves so others can conquer us. The Vikings found us easy because we were too b\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 usy fighting each other. If we\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 d once united against the Norsemen 
