\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 I will open my heart and pray as never before that you shall reach Killaloe safely and there fi\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 nd a cure for the plague,\'94\loch\f0  Gannon said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      In the morning when he awakened in the cold upstairs room, John went to the window and looked down on the stone enclosure around the graves. He could just see it past the corner of the other cottage.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The ni\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 ght before, the stone enclosure had been a ghostly rath in the yellow light of Gannon\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s lantern, the silence weighted. An owl had floated past and Gannon had not even looked up from his silent praying.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Only Herity had been at the table when they retur\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
ned to the house. He sat there still nursing a half glass of the poteen. It had occurred to John then that Herity was one of those Irish prodigies who could imbibe ruinous amounts of alcohol with only minimal evidence of it. That was a good thing to know.
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 John realized he was seeing Herity in a new light since Gannon\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s assessment \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0  a Provo, no doubt of it.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s glad I am you\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ve returned safely from the ghostly night,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Herity said. \'93\loch\f0 There\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
\hich\f0 s wild animals about, you know.\'94
