\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Samuel Benjamin Velcourt had come up through the ra\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
nks in the United States Consular Service and the U.S. Agency for International Development. Maverick tendencies had restricted his advancement but he had managed to make many military friends during his USAID days, a fact which helped him now. There were
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 ,\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  also, his reports, often praised for their insights.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      At age sixty-one, seeing the way ahead finally blocked, he had quit USAID, where he had only been on loan from the Consular Service anyway, and he ran for the Senate from Ohio. His assets were form
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 idable \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0  
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      An ability to make himself understood in almost any company and in four languages.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      A rich family willing to back his campaign.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      A wife, May, who appealed to both young and old feminists for her outspoken wit. (Older women liked her \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 also because she looked what she was, a feisty, independent grandmother.)
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The back-room support of the Ohio Democratic Machine plus that maverick record gave him immediate appeal to Independents and Liberal Republicans.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Finally, there were the cr\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 owning facts: a rich, compelling baritone voice coupled to a dignified appearance. He looked like a senator and he talked like one.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      On the platform, Samuel Benjamin Velcourt was a presence and he knew how to project himself on TV.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The effect had \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 been devastating \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0  a landslide victory in a year when Republicans were making new gains everywhere except in the presidency.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      In an Akron columnist\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s words: \'93\loch\f0 Voters were saying they liked this guy\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s style and they wanted him in the Senate to keep an ey
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 e on the bastards.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      A British observer of the election had commented: \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 The wonder is he sat so long on the back benches.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Within two months of entering the Senate, Sam Velcourt pulled out of the ruck, proving that all those years in the ranks had\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  really taught him how the system worked.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      He worked it with the hand of an impresario drawing the most from the talent available to him.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      It surprised very few to see him tapped for the vice-presidency in Prescott\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s second campaign. They needed Oh\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
io, someone with Republican appeal, an energetic campaigner with an attractive wife, who also was willing to campaign, a man with his own power base \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0 
 all of those things which really determine how candidates are chosen. Only Velcourt\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s maverick tendencie\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 s\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  bothered the national organization.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      Adam Prescott had tipped the scales. \'93\loch\f0 Let\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s park him there and see how he works. Anyway, another term in the Senate and there\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
ll be no stopping him. We might as well get him in close where we can keep an eye on hi\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 m.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 He scares the hell out of the State Department,\'94\loch\f0  a presidential aide had said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      This had amused Prescott. \'93\loch\f0 It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s good for State to be scared. But he doesn\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
t strike me as one to use an axe. A little surgery here and there, maybe, but no big poo\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 ls of blood.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Prescott\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s assessment had proved correct on all counts and, when the plague struck late in that second term, they had worked like two halves of the same machine. Velcourt\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s military friends had proved most invaluable then, an essential p\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 art of Prescott\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s own authority.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Velcourt thought of these things as he stood at the window of the Blue Room looking out toward the light traffic on Executive Avenue South. It was early evening and he had been sworn in as President less than three hou
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 rs before, a quiet ceremony at the edge of the Rose Garden, minimal fuss and only pool coverage by the media \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0 
 two reporters, one TV camera, two still cameras and one of those from the White House itself.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Velcourt knew he was going to miss the pragmat\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 ic decisiveness of his predecessor. Adam had been a tough and experienced political in-fighter, a man who kept personal doubts carefully concealed.

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      I tend to show my doubts, Velcourt thought. I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 ll have to watch that.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      A Harvard professor had once \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 told the younger Velcourt: \'93\loch\f0 The uses of power require a certain measure of inhumanity. Imagination is a piece of baggage you often can\hich\f0 
\rquote \loch\f0 t afford to carry. If you begin thinking about people in general as individuals, that gets in your way. They are clay to\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 be shaped. That\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 
s the real truth of the democratic process.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      In spite of such thoughts, or perhaps in contrast to them, Velcourt found the view in front of him pleasant. May was safe upstairs. One of their daughters had survived up in the Michigan Res\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
erve and they had only grandsons.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      It was an evening made for love songs, he decided. One of those soft evenings after a cold spell and with the promise of more warmth to come. Pastoral, Velcourt labeled it \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0 
 quietly pastoral: the cattle munching away \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
at the tall pasture that had been the White House lawn. Guitar music, that was what it needed. Everything muted, not a hint of violence. Nothing to remind him of those ranked bodies burning at the capital\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s eastern perimeter. He could see the orange glow \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 w\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 hen he looked in that direction.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The fire\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s pungent cleansing would end soon and enfolding darkness would erase the scene from sight \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0  but not from memory.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Clay, Velcourt reminded himself.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      No miracles kept Washington plague-free. It was simp\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
ly that the area was occupied by people capable of brutal decisions. Manhattan was no different and it had the added advantage of a water perimeter no longer spanned by bridges, the tunnels blocked, and that outer buffer zone with its black fire lanes.

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0    \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0   All the \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 safe\'94\loch\f0  places waiting out the plague had at least this thing in common and one other common characteristic as well: There were no mobs inside.

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The mob that had assaulted Washington\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s perimeter less than an hour after Adam\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s death had thought\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
 a few pieces of armor and some automatic weapons might win them through the Washington Barrier. The attackers had been incapable of imagining the inferno effect from flaming splashes of Newfire, the hell temperatures and immunity to ordinary retardants. 
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 A\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
lthough it provided no feelings of absolute security, Newfire was making a big difference in the landscape. Melted concrete tended to sober those who saw it. Velcourt did not try to fool himself, though: Individuals would still try to penetrate the barrie
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 r\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 s. All it took was one infected individual and the plague was past the barriers. A very tenuous way to survive, Velcourt thought.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      He turned toward the darkening room and the open door to the lighted hallway. Secret Service agents could be heard in low\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
-voiced conversation out there. The sound reminded Velcourt that there were things to do, decisions to be made.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      There was a stirring in the lighted hallway, hurrying footsteps. A Secret Service agent leaned in and said: \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Mister President?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 ll \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 be out soon,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Velcourt said. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 The East Room.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The Cabinet and the heads of the special committees had arrived with their reports for the new President. They would meet just down the hall where all the impedimenta of audiovisual presentation had been l
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 aid out. It promised to be a long session. There would be special emphasis on one particular problem \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0 
 the new Jewish Diaspora. Only a handful of diehards had remained in Israel. The ones in Brazil would have to be fed and housed. It must be a madhouse do\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 w\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
n there in Brazil, Velcourt thought. God! When will the Jews ever find a home? The ones who had stayed behind had promised to fight their way across the desert and restore the flow of Saudi oil. Foolishness! The plague had driven energy requirements to a 
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 f\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
raction of their former level. Who traveled anymore? A lot of the survivors lived communal lives. Only the Barrier Command needed great quantities of oil, and the Soviet Union was carrying most of that load.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Velcourt could hear another voice in the ha\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
llway now, the voice for which he had been delaying, Shiloh Broderick. The aging Broderick had come over from his Washington town house with a request that he be allowed to \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 brief the President.\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
 Along with the full-protocol request there had been a \'93\loch\f0 Dear\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Sam\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
 note recalling their past association. Without ever stating it openly, the note made clear who had sent Shiloh Broderick to \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 brief the President.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      On a whim (After all, I am the President!), Velcourt said: \'93\loch\f0 Send Broderick in. Tell the others to g\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
et started without us. They can hash out some of their differences before I go in.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Velcourt bent and turned on a single floor lamp over a comfortable chair and seated himself opposite it in the shadows. Broderick, when he entered, saw the setup and u\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 nderstood.
