\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Broderick sat back, steepled his fingers and put them against his lips.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Velcourt knew who Broderick represented \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0  certain very powerful \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
and very wealthy people, a large contingent in the bureaucracy and retired from it, people whose careers had been predicated on \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 being right even when they were wrong.\'94\loch\f0 
 In a bureaucracy, Velcourt had learned early, the simple fact of being right did not w\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 i\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
n popularity contests, especially if someone higher up in the hierarchy was thus proven wrong. People who gained power in a bureaucracy, Velcourt had noted, tended to be media-minded. They wanted headline items, the more dramatic the better. Simple answer
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 s\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 , no matter how wrong they might be proven later. Drama, that was the thing \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0 
 a most powerful advantage in a conference room, especially when presented in the driest and most analytical terms. Broderick had made a career on this one fact.
