\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 here been whiling away your time with a story?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      John nodded.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      Doheny patted the old man on the shoulder. \'93\loch\f0 Get along out to the entrance, Barry. Wave a hand when they come up. We\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ll join you then.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Doheny spoke to John while keeping his attent\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 ion on the old man walking away from them. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Some among us live in the hope of revenge.\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
 He cast a quick glance at John. \'93\loch\f0 Some in despair and some lost in whatever pleasures they can find \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0 \hich\f0  drink, drugs, hideous parodies of sex with no hope of progeny.\'94\loch\f0  He\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 nodded toward the old man who had taken up station in the middle of the entrance arch, his attention directed to the right. \'93\loch\f0 Barry there wants only to meet the Madman and ask one question: \hich\f0 \lquote 
\loch\f0 Are you satisfied with what you\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 ve done?\hich\f0 \rquote \'94\loch\f0  Again, Doheny glanced \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 a\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 t John. \'93\loch\f0 We\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 
re most of us beyond fatigue.\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  He cleared his throat and John thought he would spit, but Doheny swallowed. \'93\loch\f0 We have our various ways of avoiding reality. If you forced us to face it every moment of our days we\hich\f0 
\rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 d all go mad.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The rumbling o\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 f several vehicles could be heard at a distance on the street outside. The old man bent forward to stare in that direction.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      Doheny said: \'93\loch\f0 O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 Neill\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s revenge was, I suppose, his way of not facing his reality. And the terrorists who outraged him, the bom
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 b, that was their way of avoiding their reality.\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Again, he looked at John, a fixed stare. \'93\loch\f0 You\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 ll find even a bit of sympathy around for that poor Madman, O
\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 Neill.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      John rubbed his throat, unable to turn away from Doheny\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s gaze.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 If you have no \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 alternative to despair, you may explode,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Doheny said. \'93\loch\f0 
We had only the role models of our fathers, the examples in the Church and State and family \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0 \hich\f0  violent and angry and painful.\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Doheny turned toward the entrance. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
Ahhh, there they are now.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      John l\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 ooked up to see the old man waving to them. An olive-green armored car was visible in the archway beyond him.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 When you get to Killaloe,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Doheny said, \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 make them give you some fresh clothing, stuff that fits. You should be comfortable at least.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Riding toward Killaloe in the armored car, John returned again and again to that strange scene in the hospital courtyard\'85\loch\f0 
 the old man, Doheny. It had been like theater prepared only for him. To what purpose? Was it a fishing expedition aimed at O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 Neill?
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0   \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0    O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
Neill-Within remained quiescent. No sighs, no whispering, not even the echoes of screams nor the howling like that of a bereft dog. That was the most terrible sound of all \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0  the howling.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The old man in the courtyard remained bothersome. John felt\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  sympathy for him. It was the sympathy he felt for O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 
Neill. Both had suffered tragic bereavement. And what could the poor old fellow do about it? Guard a doorway? Run errands for Doheny, perhaps. Fill out his days until he died\'85\loch\f0  alone. John had not imagin\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 e
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 d old men like that in Ireland, nor for that matter any silent boys.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Tears slid down John\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s cheeks. He closed his eyes against them and when he opened them, found Father Michael staring across the back of the seat at him.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      John patted the seat bes\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 ide him. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Father, please join me.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Gently, not to awaken the sleeping boy, Father Michael disengaged himself from the cradled head and slid over the seat, clumsily bumping into John and lurching to the position beside him as the car turned a sharp cor
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 ner.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 What is it, John?\'94\loch\f0  the priest asked.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Will you hear my confession, Father?\'94\loch\f0  John whispered.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      It has come at last, Father Michael thought. He had suffered premonitions of this moment since first seeing John beside the lake \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0  that strange\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
ly depilated head, the tortured face now covered by a beard\'85\loch\f0  but the eyes still burning with terrible fires.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Yes, of course,\'94\loch\f0  Father Michael said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      John waited while the priest found his case under the seat and arrayed himself for the ancient rit\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 ual. John felt calm, calmer than he could remember since\'85\loch\f0 \hich\f0  since
\'85\loch\f0  He could not remember ever being this calm.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      Father Michael leaned toward him. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 How long has it been since your last confession, my son?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The question confused John. He had never bee\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 n to confession. John Garrech O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 Donnell had never said the words that lay now on the tip of his tongue. He uttered them:

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Forgive me, Father, for I have sinned.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Yes, my son. How have you sinned?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Father\'85\loch\f0  I have John Roe O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 Neill within me.\loch\af0\dbch\af11\hich\f0 \'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      A blank expression swept over the priest\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s face. He whispered hoarsely: \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 You\'85\loch\f0  you are O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 Neill?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      John stared at him. Why didn\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 t the priest understand? \'93\loch\f0 No, Father. I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 m John O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 Donnell. But I have O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
\hich\f0 Neill within me.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Father Michael\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s eyes wen\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
t wide, a glazed look of fascination. He had learned his psychology from a good Jesuit, Father Ambrose Dreyfus, a doctor and an expert in Freud and Jung and Adler and Reich and the permutations between. The concept of schizophrenia was not foreign to Fath
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 r Michael. But this! The enormity\'85\loch\f0 \hich\f0  the danger\'85
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The habits of the confessional preserved him.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Yes, my son. Please continue.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Continue? John sat in bewilderment. How could he continue? He had said it all. He felt like a raped woman carrying t\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 he rapist\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 
s child and being asked by a male gynecologist: \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 And what other symptoms do you have?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      When John remained silent, Father Michael asked: \'93\loch\f0 Does O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 Neill wish to confess through you?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      John sensed the terrible stirring within, the start of t\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 he howl. No! He pressed his hands against his ears, knowing as he did it that nothing would keep out the sounds of that awful anguish.

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      Father Michael sensed the dismay and said in his most calming voice: \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 You wish to confess for yourself?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      John h\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 eld himself still for several long heartbeats, lowering his hands only when he sensed the calmness returning.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 For myself,\'94\loch\f0  he whispered.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Father Michael lurched into John as the armored car negotiated a rutted turn, growling loudly in reduced gea\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
rs. The priest glanced forward: The driver and guard appeared unaware of the drama in the rear. The boy still slept.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      His mouth close to the priest\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s ear, John whispered: \'93\loch\f0 It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s a terrible burden, Father.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Father Michael felt that he had to agree. \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 An awesome sense of compassion swept over him. The poor man! Driven insane\'85\loch\f0 
 yet coming here in the shy and persistent identity of John O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 Donnell. Wanting to help. A maddened creature within him trying to undo the terrible wrong.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Help me, Father,\'94\loch\f0  Joh\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 n pleaded.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Father Michael placed a hand on John\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s head, feeling the neck muscles stiffen at the touch and then relax as John bent his head.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      How could such anguish be relieved? the priest wondered. What penance could possibly be assigned? He sense\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 d the other persona, O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 Neill, waiting for him to speak.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Please, Father!\'94\loch\f0  John whispered.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Father Michael went into automatic, whispering the familiar absolution and benediction. Only the penance remained. What could he assign? How could anyone he\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 lp this poor creature?
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      God help me! Father Michael prayed.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The solution filled his awareness and he felt blessed calm as he spoke.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 John, you must do everything in your power to find a cure for this plague. That is your penance.\'94\loch\f0  He made the\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  sign of the cross on John\hich\f0 
\rquote \loch\f0 s forehead, feeling that he had personally assumed John\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s burden. What priest had ever before been asked to keep such an awful secret under the seal of the confessional? Perhaps only Christ Himself had known such a weight. Fathe\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 r\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  Michael could not tell.

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      John sat in silent withdrawal, his eyes closed tightly, fists clenched in his lap. Father Michael sensed the man\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s disturbance but could not hear the howling.
