\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The coming of the mob ignited a strange new personality in Kevin O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 Donnell. Doheny glimpsed it only briefly as he and the other principals of the trial were \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
taken out under guard, ordered locked up in the rooms under the castle\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s tower. Kevin turned first to the jury and told them to find weapons. They no longer were jurymen but \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 soldiers at Armageddon!
\'94\loch\f0  A distant look of dreaming took over Kevin\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s face. He g\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 stured broadly with his right hand and took up the jar with Alex Coleman\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s head, saying:
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Come watch it, Alex! This is the moment for which I was born.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Herity\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s corpse he ignored except to topple the chair and body as he left the room, striding \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 along, Doheny thought, like God Almighty.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      As his party was rushed across the courtyard by the guards, Doheny noted that the gates had been closed, shutting off the view of the lough. The cries of the mob were loud in the courtyard, though \hich\f0 \endash 
\loch\f0  an all-mal\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 e animal demanding its due. Some were screaming: \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 The cure! Give us the cure!\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Now what had made them think a cure already had been produced?
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The guards hustled Doheny into the bailey behind John, Father Michael and the boy, but not before he gli\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
mpsed Kevin once more striding along the parapet of the old castle. Kevin did not deign to glance down at the mob that was shouting out there. His manner said he considered them a pack of brutes hungering for the food of the gods, the manna that only he c
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 o\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 ntrolled.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 Give us the cure! Give us O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 Neill!\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Doheny and his companions were herded to the door at the head of the dungeon keep. The guards thrust them through the door and slammed it behind them, not bothering to lock them in their individual c
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 ells. They stumbled down the long stairs to the chant of the mob, which had returned to its original demand: \'93\loch\f0 O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 Neill! O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 Neill!\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      They stopped in the room of jumbled discards at the bottom of the stairs. Father Michael brushed cobwebs off his face. Joh\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
n returned to his cell and entered it. The boy climbed up on the broken sofa trying to peer out of a barred window high on the wall. The mob sound was loud there. John emerged presently wearing the clothing the guards had made him discard. It was damp and
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 marked with patches of slime, which he tried to wipe away with the lab coat.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Why did they take away my clothes?\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  he asked, his voice distant. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Was it because the priest had a knife?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s all right, John,\'94\loch\f0  Father Michael said. He put a hand on \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 John\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s shoulder. There was a deep trembling in the man.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The boy was clambering across the stack of lumber in the corner, still unable to reach the barred window.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Give it up, lad,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Doheny said. \'93\loch\f0 You\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ll fall and hurt yourself.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      A great roar c\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 ame from the mob. There was a quick burst of automatic weapons fire, then silence. Even the chanting stopped.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 What do you suppose they\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 re doing out there?\'94\loch\f0  Father Michael asked.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 Sharpening their scythes, their pruning hooks and pitchforks, most\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0  likely,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Doheny said. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Preparing for the jacquerie.
\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The last word was almost drowned in another mob roar that shook the room.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      John seemed not to hear. He was staring up at the boy on the stack of lumber, remembering him as he had been during th\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
eir tramp across the countryside. There was a feral energy in the boy now, a tension and purpose about him.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Father Michael!\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  the boy called, his voice low and intense. \'93\loch\f0 There\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s a tunnel back here!\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 A tunnel is it?\'94\loch\f0  The priest scrambled over the\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
 discards toward the boy, pulling boards aside and peering behind him. He lifted his head and spoke to Doheny: \'93\loch\f0 There\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s fresh air! It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s a way out!\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
 He pulled out more boards, exposing a low opening. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Bring John!\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Doheny took John\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s arm. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Come along.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 I can\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 t,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  John said. \'93\loch\f0 O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 Neill doesn\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 t want to go.\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
 He swept a wild gaze around the dark room. \'93\loch\f0 Why have they come? I don\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 t\'85\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The rest of it was lost in another roar from the crowd and more gunfire. The mob sounds became a rhythmic assault, no wo\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 rds, just hoarse and inarticulate noises \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0 
 a gigantic grunting that filled Doheny with terror. Father Michael darted across the junk and took John\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s right arm.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 I think we\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ll have to drag him,\'94\loch\f0  Doheny said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Come with us, John,\'94\loch\f0  the priest said. \loch\af0\dbch\af11\hich\f0 \'93\loch\f0 We\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 re trying to save you. Aren\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 t we, Fin?
\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 We are that.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 Will you take O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 Neill, too?\'94\loch\f0  John asked.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Of course!\'94\loch\f0  Father Michael said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 But where is he?\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  John asked. \'93\loch\f0 He was in the jar on the table. I don\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 t see him.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 He\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s already \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 gone on,\'94\loch\f0  Doheny said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Oh.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      John allowed himself to be led in a stumbling scramble across the junk and around the stacked wood. The boy awaited them there in an arched passage of moldy stone. The floor underfoot was slippery with slime and there
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  were upturned stones, puddles of water. The smell of sewage seeped through the cracks.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Doheny listened to the mob sounds overhead. The thumping of many feet could be felt. The gunfire had been reduced to a few scattered shots. Father Michael pushed J\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
ohn down the passage ahead of him. The boy led. There was faint light ahead, but it was dark and odorous in the tunnel. Presently, they saw patchy daylight ahead framed in bushes and partly blocked by an iron grating. Father Michael waved them all to a st
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 o\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 p at the grating, listening. The mob was a dim sound behind them. No more gunfire. Doheny realized they had stopped in a small stone hut piled on both sides with rusty gardening tools \hich\f0 
\endash \loch\f0  hoes, rakes, shovels, trowels, hand cultivators.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Rows of earthenw\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
are pots had fallen from rotted shelves and the broken shards ground underfoot with bits and pieces of wire and rust-eaten cans. Daylight leaked through chinks in the stone and through a doorway partly blocked by a gate of rusty iron and thick shrubbery.

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0     John closed his eyes and hugged his arms close. He breathed in shallow gasps, flexing and tensing his fingers.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The boy crept out under the shrubbery and could be heard moving around the hut.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Doheny touched one of John\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s hands and was rewarded\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  with an abrupt upward jerking of the head, eyes wide open and glaring.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      Father Michael waved for Doheny to stay and went after the boy. He returned in a moment to say: \'93\loch\f0 This hut sits beside an old glass house and there\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s an overgrown trail that seems \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 to go out to the road. The boy\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s gone on ahead to scout it.\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  The priest nodded at John. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Is he saying anything?\'94

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s fascinating,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Doheny said, caught up in clinical observation of John. \'93\loch\f0 
Controlled displacement of identity, I think. He knows there\hich\f0 \rquote \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 s another persona present and may even talk to it but I doubt he can overcome the dissociation.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      Father Michael shuddered. \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Whatever shall we do with him?\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      At Father Michael\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s words, John squatted on the filthy floor and hid his face against his \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 knees, crouching like a hunted animal in its den.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      It would kill him to restore him to O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 Neill, Doheny thought.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Where had that boy got to? A sudden chilling thought welled up in Doheny\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s awareness: Kevin had said the boy was ready to spring the ha\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 ngman\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s trap under O\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 Neill. Had the boy gone to alert Kevin or the mob?
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      A noise at the doorway brought his attention away from John. The boy slipped through the opening. He appeared subdued, more like his silent self. He gestured for them to follow hi\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
m and went back outside. The bushes swished with his passage.
