\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Kate liked to sit by the window of her new room on the top floor of Huddersfiel\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 d\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s Administration Building when she nursed her baby. She knew the big mirror across from her was actually a window permitting the lines of men passing in the outside corridor to peer in at her. She had only to look up into the mirror to see what the pass
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 i\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 ng viewers saw. She found it odd that she felt no embarrassment to know men watched her suckling Gilla at her breast.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      What a beautiful infant Gilla was becoming \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0  the way her feet kicked, the wrinkles smoothing out, the look of alertness beginning to \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
appear in her eyes. She was going to have red hair, fine and silky the way Kate\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s own mother\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s hair had been. How precious this infant was!
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      There had been a bad few days when they brought the serum and told her their decision. So cold-blooded they had\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
 sounded, and she had screamed at the hulking Doctor Beckett, that ugly, lantern-jawed man with his gigantic mouth and the awful words coming out of it.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 You and your husband can have many daughters, Mrs. Browder. You\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 ve already demonstrated that, and\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
, with our new techniques of genetic control, we can insure that you have only daughters.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Men in white coats had been holding her all through this, keeping her away from Gilla, not even letting Stephen be with her.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Beckett, an angry light in his\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0  eyes, had shouted at her: \'93\loch\f0 We\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 ve only enough serum for you, Mrs. Browder!\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Give it to Gilla!\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 No! If your blood picks up fast enough, we can give your blood serum to the baby. We may be able to save her.\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 May be!\'94\loch\f0  she had screamed.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 But there had been no resisting the strong men and that was the way it had been \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0 
 her arm strapped down, a needle in it. She had lived through dreadful days, rocking Gilla and sobbing, fearing every moment that she would see the terrible plague symptoms i\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 n\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  the infant.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      After the injection, Stephen had been permitted to come to her. Sounding almost like a priest, he had pleaded with her to \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 be calm and accept whatever God gives us.\'94\loch\f0 
 Stephen and the drugs had tried to be soothing but she could still think\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
 back to that time and feel the awful tremors in her stomach. Gilla at her breast restored the calm. The blood serum had been produced in time. And now, everyone was giving blood serum. It was spreading out across the world like a wave.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The door behin\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
d Kate opened and she heard Stephen enter, the cautious movements. She saw him in the mirror, the way he looked at the mirror, not liking it but accepting the necessity. He had seen the long lines out there, the avid eyes peering in at mother and child. S
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 t\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 ephen was resisting extensions of the viewing time but Kate was not sure this was right.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      In the whole world, the ratio of men to women was said to be ten thousand to one or worse. Here in England, of course, it was worse, although women saved by resou\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
rceful men were still being found and inoculated. A great new barracks establishment had been set up at Aldershot where the women were being protected. Kate wondered how those women felt about her own special status \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0 
 the first one saved. The Woman in the\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
Tank. She knew there was pressure to get her back to Ireland, but she and Stephen were agreed that it was not yet safe. There were still Beach Boys with weapons roaming loose. And there were even women survivors being found in Ireland, although the storie
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 s\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  of their tribulations filled Kate with horror. Troubles! That was all Ireland ever seemed to experience.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      I was lucky.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      She sensed the power in her position. She was a symbol in a world agog with the announcements being made from Kangsha and Hudde\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 rsfield. Despite her nurse\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s training, she found some of the things being said almost too much to accept. Was it possible that she and Gilla might live five thousand years or more? They were saying that they could assure from conception whether a baby wou
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 l\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 d be male or female and that the female birth ratio was going to be held at \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 very high levels\'94\loch\f0  until the balance had been restored.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Kate found the thought of a five-thousand-year lifetime difficult to imagine. Five thousand years. What would she do wi\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
th all of that time? There would have to be more than producing babies, although she knew this would be her duty for years to come. Duty! Hard from the mouth of a priest, it was a male word\'85\loch\f0 
 a legal judgment. There would be no escaping it. She and Stephen\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 must produce more daughters.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      There were compensations, though. Kate found she rather liked her present female eminence, sensing that she must take advantage of it while she could. It would not endure in the face of this new genetic science. While it l
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 asted, it was exciting. The men paying court to her! That was the only way to describe it: courting. Not flirtation or simple attempts at seduction; the men were serious and it enraged Stephen.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Kate saw in the mirror that Stephen had taken a chair by \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
the smaller window behind her, the one looking out over the Huddersfield campus. The way he pretended to sit there reading his book! He was making a statement to the passing viewers: \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 This one is mine!\'94
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      She liked that. Kate could feel the love of Step\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
hen, a warm current all through her body. A bond of terrible strength had been welded between them in the confinement of the isolation tank. She knew tiny detailed things about him now, weaknesses and strengths.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      He saved my life.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Each suckling mo\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 vement of the baby drawing life\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s own milk from her breast amplified the waves of loving heat she felt for Stephen. She sensed it deep in her abdomen.

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      The courting men were interesting, though, especially the Russian, Lepikov. What a charming man. Old\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
 World charm. How amusing he was, lifting those thick black eyebrows at her, rolling his dark eyes. Poor man. His entire family dead somewhere in the Soviet Union. She felt so sad when she thought of it. How she wanted to cradle his head on her breast and
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 comfort him. Stephen would never permit that, though.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Its stomach full, the baby turned away from her breast and drifted into sleep, a tiny bubble of milk on her lips. Kate smiled down at her daughter, taking her time about covering herself. Gilla was
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  such a fascinating person to watch: the miniature face in innocent repose, that little dimple on her left cheek. What a blessing. What a miracle.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Kate glanced at her wristwatch: 10:10 A.M. She held the watch to her left ear. It still ran perfectly af\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
ter all this time. She thought sadly of her mother presenting the watch to her the day Kate had gone off to nursing school.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Ahhhh, Momma, I wish you could see your own granddaughter, your own flesh and blood, alive and happy.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Perhaps it was a ble\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0 ssing, though, that Momma could only look down from heaven at this scene. A terrible price was being asked of women. Secondary husbands\'85\loch\f0 
 and even more. Kate felt a thrilling shiver at what she might be asked to accept. And how strange it was that the two \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 p\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
riests disagreed on this question. She dared not even raise the problem with Stephen. She knew how he would react. The tiny steel chamber with its ever-sounding airpump had created a singleness between them, though, and she suspected that Stephen knew wha
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 t\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0  she was thinking.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 \hich\f0      \'93\loch\f0 The priest\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 \hich\f0 s here,\'94\loch\f0  Stephen said.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Just from his tone and before she looked up, Kate knew it was Father Cavanagh and not Father Michael. Stephen liked Father Michael and barely tolerated Cavanagh. Kate found this difficult to u\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 
nderstand. Father Michael had married them back in Ireland, but he was such a hard man, that horse face never smiling. Father Cavanagh, however, was jolly and soothing. He spoke of a happy God who wanted pleasant things for his flock. Father Michael was s
\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 t\hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 ern and threatening. He liked to talk philosophy with Stephen. It got so boring at times.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0      Father Cavanagh brought up a chair and seated himself in front of Kate, their knees almost touching.
